[src:rspec/3-13-rspec-mocks] rspec-mocks helps to control the context in a code example by letting you set known return values, fake implementations of methods, and even set expectations that specific messages are received by an object.
[src:rspec/3-13-rspec-mocks] You can do these three things on test doubles that rspec-mocks creates for you on the fly, or you can do them on objects that are part of your system.
[src:rspec/3-13-rspec-mocks] A test double is an object that stands in for another object in your system during a code example.
[src:rspec/3-13-rspec-mocks] Most of the time you will want some confidence that your doubles resemble an existing object in your system.
[src:rspec/3-13-rspec-mocks] Verifying doubles are provided for this purpose.
[src:rspec/3-13-rspec-mocks] If the existing object is available, they will prevent you from adding stubs and expectations for methods that do not exist or that have invalid arguments.
[src:rspec/3-13-rspec-mocks] Verifying doubles have some clever tricks to enable you to both test in isolation without your dependencies loaded while still being able to validate them against real objects.
[src:rspec/3-13-rspec-mocks] This tells the `die` object to return the value `3` when it receives the `roll` message.
[src:rspec/3-13-rspec-mocks] This example specifies that the `account` object sends the `logger` the `account_closed` message (with itself as an argument) when it receives the `close` message.
[src:rspec/3-13-rspec-mocks] The documentation for rspec-mocks is a work in progress.
[src:rspec/3-13-rspec-mocks] We’ll be adding Cucumber features over time, and clarifying existing ones.
[src:rspec/3-13-rspec-mocks] If you have specific features you’d like to see added, find the existing documentation incomplete or confusing, or, better yet, wish to write a missing Cucumber feature yourself, please submit an issue or a pull request.
[src:rspec/behavior-driven-development] BDD involves use of a domain-specific language (DSL) using natural-language constructs (e.g., English-like sentences) that can express the behavior and the expected outcomes.
[src:rspec/behavior-driven-development] BDD encourages collaboration among developers, quality assurance experts, and customer representatives in a software project.
[src:rspec/behavior-driven-development] It encourages teams to use conversation and concrete examples to formalize a shared understanding of how the application should behave.
[src:rspec/behavior-driven-development] BDD is considered an effective practice especially when the *problem space* is complex.
[src:rspec/behavior-driven-development] A common misconception regarding BDD is that it supposedly is a refinement of test-driven development (TDD).
[src:rspec/behavior-driven-development] While it was originally derived from TDD practices, the sole purpose of BDD is to gain a *shared understanding* of the problem space and find a way to write this down in a Business Language, using Real data, whilst being Intention revealing, Essential and Focused (BRIEF).
[src:rspec/behavior-driven-development] BDD combines the techniques of TDD with ideas from domain-driven design and object-oriented analysis and design to provide software development and management teams with shared tools and a shared process to collaborate on software development.
[src:rspec/behavior-driven-development] At a high level, BDD is an idea about how software development should be managed by both business interests and technical insight.
[src:rspec/behavior-driven-development] Its *practice* involves use of specialized tools.
[src:rspec/behavior-driven-development] Some tools specifically for BDD can be used for TDD.
[src:rspec/behavior-driven-development] The tools automate the ubiquitous language.
[src:rspec/behavior-driven-development] BDD is a process by which DSL structured natural-language statements are converted into executable tests.
[src:rspec/behavior-driven-development] The result is executable specification eventually forming Living Documentation: Requirements that are also the first acceptance tests that drive your software development (Acceptance test-driven development).
[src:rspec/behavior-driven-development] Starting from this point, many people developed BDD frameworks over a period of years, finally framing it in terms of a communication and collaboration framework for developers, QA and non-technical or business participants in a software project.
[src:rspec/behavior-driven-development] BDD suggests that software tests should be named in terms of desired *behavior*.
[src:rspec/behavior-driven-development] Borrowing from agile software development the "desired behavior" in this case consists of the requirements set by the business — that is, the desired behavior that has business value for whatever entity commissioned the software unit under construction.
[src:rspec/behavior-driven-development] Within BDD practice, this is referred to as BDD being an "outside-in" activity.
[src:rspec/behavior-driven-development] TDD does not differentiate tests in terms of high-level software requirements, low-level technical details or anything in between.
[src:rspec/behavior-driven-development] One way of looking at BDD therefore, is that it is an evolution of TDD which makes more specific choices.
[src:rspec/behavior-driven-development] Another BDD suggestion relates to *how* the desired behavior should be specified.
[src:rspec/behavior-driven-development] BDD suggests using a semi-formal format for behavioral specification which is borrowed from user story specifications from the field of object-oriented analysis and design.
[src:rspec/behavior-driven-development] The scenario aspect of this format may be regarded as an application of Hoare logic to behavioral specification of software using the domain-specific language.
[src:rspec/behavior-driven-development] BDD suggests that business analysts and software developers should collaborate in this area and should specify behavior in terms of user stories, which are each explicitly documented.
[src:rspec/behavior-driven-development] BDD does not require how this information is formatted, but it does suggest that a team should decide on a relatively simple, standardized format with the above elements.
[src:rspec/behavior-driven-development] It also suggests that the scenarios should be phrased declaratively rather than imperatively — in the business language, with no reference to elements of the UI through which the interactions take place.
[src:rspec/behavior-driven-development] This format is referred to in Cucumber as the Gherkin language.
[src:rspec/behavior-driven-development] BDD borrows the concept of the *ubiquitous language* from domain driven design.
[src:rspec/behavior-driven-development] A ubiquitous language is a (semi-)formal language that is shared by all members of a software development team — both software developers and non-technical personnel.
[src:rspec/behavior-driven-development] The language in question is both used and developed by all team members as a common means of discussing the domain of the software in question.
[src:rspec/behavior-driven-development] In this way BDD becomes a vehicle for communication between all the different roles in a software project.
[src:rspec/behavior-driven-development] A common risk with software development includes communication breakdowns between Developers and Business Stakeholders.
[src:rspec/behavior-driven-development] BDD uses the specification of desired behavior as a ubiquitous language for the project Team members.
[src:rspec/behavior-driven-development] This is the reason that BDD insists on a semi-formal language for behavioral specification: some formality is a requirement for being a ubiquitous language.
[src:rspec/behavior-driven-development] In addition, having such a ubiquitous language creates a domain model of specifications, so that specifications may be reasoned about formally.
[src:rspec/behavior-driven-development] This model is also the basis for the different BDD-supporting software tools that are available.
[src:rspec/behavior-driven-development] The example given above establishes a user story for a software system under development.
[src:rspec/behavior-driven-development] This user story identifies a stakeholder, a business effect and a business value.
[src:rspec/behavior-driven-development] It also describes several scenarios, each with a precondition, trigger and expected outcome.
[src:rspec/behavior-driven-development] Each of these parts is exactly identified by the more formal part of the language (the term **Given** might be considered a keyword, for example) and may therefore be processed in some way by a tool that understands the formal parts of the ubiquitous language.
[src:rspec/behavior-driven-development] Most BDD applications use text-based DSLs and specification approaches.
[src:rspec/behavior-driven-development] However, graphical modeling of integration scenarios has also been applied successfully in practice, e.g., for testing purposes.
[src:rspec/behavior-driven-development] Much like TDD, BDD may involve using specialized tooling.
[src:rspec/behavior-driven-development] BDD requires not only test code as does TDD, but also a document that describes behavior in a more human-readable language.
[src:rspec/behavior-driven-development] This requires a two-step process for executing the tests, reading and parsing the descriptions, and reading the test code and finding the corresponding test implementation to execute.
[src:rspec/behavior-driven-development] This process makes BDD more laborious for developers.
[src:rspec/behavior-driven-development] Proponents suggest that due to its human-readable nature the value of those documents extends to a relatively non-technical audience, and can hence serve as a communication means for describing requirements ("features").
[src:rspec/behavior-driven-development] In principle, a BDD support tool is a testing framework for software, much like the tools that support TDD.
[src:rspec/behavior-driven-development] However, where TDD tools tend to be quite free-format in what is allowed for specifying tests, BDD tools are linked to the definition of the ubiquitous language.
[src:rspec/behavior-driven-development] The ubiquitous language allows business analysts to document behavioral requirements in a way that will also be understood by developers.
[src:rspec/behavior-driven-development] The principle of BDD support tooling is to make these same requirements documents directly executable as a collection of tests.
[src:rspec/behavior-driven-development] If this cannot be achieved because of reasons related to the technical tool that enables the execution of the specifications, then either the style of writing the behavioral requirements must be altered or the tool must be changed.
[src:rspec/behavior-driven-development] A separate subcategory of behavior-driven development is formed by tools that use specifications as an input language rather than user stories.
[src:rspec/behavior-driven-development] Specification tools don't use user stories as an input format for test scenarios but rather use functional specifications for units that are being tested.
[src:rspec/behavior-driven-development] These specifications often have a more technical nature than user stories and are usually less convenient for communication with business personnel than are user stories.
[src:rspec/behavior-driven-development] Such a specification may exactly specify the behavior of the component being tested, but is less meaningful to a business user.
[src:rspec/behavior-driven-development] As a result, specification-based testing is seen in BDD practice as a complement to story-based testing and operates at a lower level.
[src:rspec/behavior-driven-development] Specification testing is often seen as a replacement for free-format unit testing.
[src:rspec/behavior-driven-development] The "three amigos", also referred to as a "Specification Workshop", is a meeting where the product owner discusses the requirement in the form of specification by example with different stakeholders like the QA and development team.
[src:rspec/behavior-driven-development] The key goal for this discussion is to trigger conversation and identify any missing specifications.
[src:rspec/behavior-driven-development] The discussion also gives a platform for QA, development team and product owner to converge and hear out each other's perspective to enrich the requirement and also make sure if they are building the right product.
[src:rspec/documentation] RSpec is composed of multiple libraries, which are designed to work together, or can be used independently with other testing tools like Cucumber or Minitest.
[src:rspec/documentation] The API documentation contains details about all public APIs supported by RSpec.
[src:rspec/documentation] We consider these the primary docs and will treat these APIs according to the policies of Semantic Versioning.
[src:rspec/documentation] We encourage you to use only public APIs as private APIs may change in any release without warning.
[src:rspec/documentation] If you have a use case not supported by the existing public APIs, please ask and we'll be glad to add an API for you or make an existing private API public.
[src:rspec/documentation] RSpec is also documented through executable examples written in Gherkin.
[src:rspec/documentation] The examples are written in an "end-to-end" style demonstrating the use of various RSpec features in the context of executable spec files.
[src:rspec/documentation] They are a good resource for getting a survey of what RSpec is capable of and seeing how the pieces can be used together, but for detailed documentation about a particular API or feature, we recommend the API docs.
[src:rspec/documentation] These feature files are executed via Cucumber in our CI process to ensure they are always up-to-date with the current code base.
[src:rspec/documentation] Previously our gherkin examples could be read on RelishApp but currently this service is unavailable.
[src:rspec/documentation] We thank Matt Wynne for his contribution hosting these over the years, and we now host these ourselves via the table above.
[src:rspec/rspec-expectations] rspec-expectations is used to define expected outcomes.
[src:rspec/rspec-expectations] Note: You can also use `expect(..).to_not` instead of `expect(..).not_to`.
[src:rspec/rspec-expectations] One is an alias to the other, so you can use whichever reads better to you.
[src:rspec/rspec-expectations] RSpec ships with a number of built-in matchers and a DSL for writing custom matchers.
[src:rspec/rspec-expectations] The documentation for rspec-expectations is a work in progress.
[src:rspec/rspec] RSpec was started as an experiment by Steven Baker in 2005 along with his team members Dave Astels, Aslak Hellesøy and David Chelimsky.
[src:rspec/rspec] Chelimsky was responsible for developing the RSpec-Rails which facilitated the integration with Ruby on Rails.
[src:rspec/rspec] RSpec 1.0 came out in May 2007 which contained many prime features of RSpec which are being included in the latest releases too.
[src:rspec/rspec] However, due to some technical issues such as testing speed, it was discontinued later.
[src:rspec/rspec] The third version of RSpec i.e. the RSpec 3 was released in July 2014 which had many new features like verify doubles, composable matchers and many more.
[src:rspec/rspec] As mentioned above, RSpec provides a domain-specific language to describe the behavior of objects.
[src:rspec/rspec] The keywords used in RSpec are similar to the ones used in other languages and/or TDD frameworks.
[src:rspec/rspec] There are many such keywords which are used in the same context but with the similar names.
[src:rspec/rspec] The syntax of RSpec provides the ease of readability and describes the behavior of the code thereby providing freedom to the programmer.
[src:rspec/rspec] Every testing framework works in the following flow - given some context, when some event occurs, what outcome is expected.
[src:rspec/rspec] The methods like describe(), context() and it() form the analogy and the skeleton respectively of the test code.
[src:rspec/rspec] The describe() method is used to describe a class, method or an example group.
[src:rspec/rspec] This is the outer block which actually contains the test code and it depicts the characteristics of the code enclosed in it.
[src:rspec/rspec] This method takes a number of arguments and an optional block.
[src:rspec/rspec] However, normally one or two arguments are used to describe the behavior of the example group.
[src:rspec/rspec] The first argument represents the reference to the class or module whereas the second argument is optional whose datatype would be String.
[src:rspec/rspec] The example groups can be nested as well.
[src:rspec/rspec] The context() block is used to describe the context in which the class or method mentioned in the describe block is being used.
[src:rspec/rspec] This can be considered as an alias to the word describe() in this scenario and they both can be used interchangeably.
[src:rspec/rspec] Generally, describe() is used for things and context() is used for contexts.
[src:rspec/rspec] It helps to venture out different outcomes in different scenarios.
[src:rspec/rspec] Using context() makes it easier to scan a spec file and makes it clear what it relates to.
[src:rspec/rspec] It is a RSpec method which describes the specifications of the sample in the context.
[src:rspec/rspec] The it() block takes a string as an argument and the string after the 'it' keyword can be considered as the function that the block is expected to perform or in other words it can be considered as a test case.
[src:rspec/rspec] In RSpec, an *expectation* is a statement expressing the state that something is expected to be in, at a particular point in the execution of a code example.
[src:rspec/rspec] RSpec uses a simple framework and keywords like *should()* and *should_not()* to express expectations.
[src:rspec/rspec] It supports matchers, that is objects that try to match an expected outcome, for common operations as well as uncommon expressions.
[src:rspec/rspec] RSpec provides a library called RSpec::Mocks in order to create test doubles that facilitate focusing on roles, interface discovery, but most of all making progress without implemented dependencies thereby providing isolation from coupling and non determinism.
[src:rspec/rspec] RSpec has support from numerous text editors and coverage suites.
[src:rspec/rspec] RSpec also provides a number of utilities and extension points to support extending RSpec to meet domain-specific needs.
[src:rspec/rspec] For instance, using Metadata associated with groups and examples for the purpose of reporting, using global configuration to assign before and after blocks to every example group, using macros etc.
[src:rspec/ruby-programming-language] Ruby is interpreted, high-level, and dynamically typed; its interpreter uses garbage collection and just-in-time compilation.
[src:rspec/ruby-programming-language] It supports multiple programming paradigms, including procedural, object-oriented, and functional programming.
[src:rspec/ruby-programming-language] According to the creator, Ruby was influenced by Perl, Smalltalk, Eiffel, Ada, BASIC, and Lisp.
[src:rspec/ruby-programming-language] According to Matsumoto, Ruby was conceived in 1993.
[src:rspec/ruby-programming-language] Matsumoto described Ruby's design as resembling a simple Lisp language at its core, with an object system like that of Smalltalk, blocks inspired by higher-order functions, and practical utility like that of Perl.
[src:rspec/ruby-programming-language] The name "Ruby" originated during an online chat session between Matsumoto and Keiju Ishitsuka on 24 February 1993, before any code had been written.
[src:rspec/ruby-programming-language] Two names were initially proposed: "Coral" and "Ruby".
[src:rspec/ruby-programming-language] Matsumoto chose the latter in a subsequent email to Ishitsuka.
[src:rspec/ruby-programming-language] He also noted that one factor influencing the choice of the name was that a colleague's birthstone was ruby.
[src:rspec/ruby-programming-language] The first public release of Ruby 0.95 was announced on Japanese domestic newsgroups on 21 December 1995.
[src:rspec/ruby-programming-language] Subsequently, three more versions of Ruby were released in two days.
[src:rspec/ruby-programming-language] The release coincided with the launch of the Japanese-language *ruby-list* mailing list, which was the first mailing list for the new language.
[src:rspec/ruby-programming-language] Already present at this stage of development were many of the features familiar in later releases of Ruby, including object-oriented design, classes with inheritance, mixins, iterators, closures, exception handling and garbage collection.
[src:rspec/ruby-programming-language] After the release of Ruby 0.95 in 1995, several stable versions of Ruby were released in these years.
[src:rspec/ruby-programming-language] In 1997, the first article about Ruby was published on the Web.
[src:rspec/ruby-programming-language] In the same year, Matsumoto was hired by netlab.jp to work on Ruby as a full-time developer.
[src:rspec/ruby-programming-language] In 1998, the Ruby Application Archive was launched by Matsumoto, along with a simple English-language homepage for Ruby.
[src:rspec/ruby-programming-language] In 1999, the first English language mailing list *ruby-talk* began, which signaled a growing interest in the language outside Japan.
[src:rspec/ruby-programming-language] In this same year, Matsumoto and Keiju Ishitsuka wrote the first book on Ruby, *The Object-oriented Scripting Language Ruby* (オブジェクト指向スクリプト言語 Ruby), which was published in Japan in October 1999.
[src:rspec/ruby-programming-language] It would be followed in the early 2000s by around 20 books on Ruby published in Japanese.
[src:rspec/ruby-programming-language] By 2000, Ruby was more popular than Python in Japan.
[src:rspec/ruby-programming-language] In September 2000, the first English language book *Programming Ruby* was printed, which was later freely released to the public, further widening the adoption of Ruby amongst English speakers.
[src:rspec/ruby-programming-language] In early 2002, the English-language *ruby-talk* mailing list was receiving more messages than the Japanese-language *ruby-list*, demonstrating Ruby's increasing popularity in the non-Japanese speaking world.
[src:rspec/ruby-programming-language] Ruby 1.8 was initially released in August 2003, was stable for a long time, and was retired in June 2013.
[src:rspec/ruby-programming-language] Although deprecated, there is still code based on it.
[src:rspec/ruby-programming-language] Ruby 1.8 is only partially compatible with Ruby 1.9.
[src:rspec/ruby-programming-language] Ruby 1.8 has been the subject of several industry standards.
[src:rspec/ruby-programming-language] It was accepted as a Japanese Industrial Standard (JIS X 3017) in 2011 and an international standard (ISO/IEC 30170) in 2012.
[src:rspec/ruby-programming-language] Around 2005, interest in the Ruby language surged in tandem with Ruby on Rails, a web framework written in Ruby.
[src:rspec/ruby-programming-language] Rails is frequently credited with increasing awareness of Ruby.
[src:rspec/ruby-programming-language] Effective with Ruby 1.9.3, released 31 October 2011, Ruby switched from being dual-licensed under the Ruby License and the GPL to being dual-licensed under the Ruby License and the two-clause BSD license.
[src:rspec/ruby-programming-language] Adoption of 1.9 was slowed by changes from 1.8 that required many popular third party gems to be rewritten.
[src:rspec/ruby-programming-language] Ruby 2.0 was intended to be fully backward compatible with Ruby 1.9.3.
[src:rspec/ruby-programming-language] As of the official 2.0.0 release on 24 February 2013, there were only five known incompatibilities.
[src:rspec/ruby-programming-language] Starting with 2.1.0, Ruby's versioning policy changed to be more similar to semantic versioning, although it differs slightly in that minor version increments may be API incompatible.
[src:rspec/ruby-programming-language] Ruby 2.2.0 includes speed-ups, bugfixes, and library updates and removes some deprecated APIs.
[src:rspec/ruby-programming-language] Most notably, Ruby 2.2.0 introduces changes to memory handling – an incremental garbage collector, support for garbage collection of symbols and the option to compile directly against jemalloc.
[src:rspec/ruby-programming-language] It also contains experimental support for using vfork(2) with system() and spawn(), and added support for the Unicode 7.0 specification.
[src:rspec/ruby-programming-language] Since version 2.2.1, Ruby MRI performance on PowerPC64 was improved.
[src:rspec/ruby-programming-language] Features that were made obsolete or removed include callcc, the DL library, Digest::HMAC, lib/rational.rb, lib/complex.rb, GServer, Logger::Application as well as various C API functions.
[src:rspec/ruby-programming-language] Ruby 2.3.0 includes many performance improvements, updates, and bugfixes including changes to Proc#call, Socket and IO use of exception keywords, Thread#name handling, default passive Net::FTP connections, and Rake being removed from stdlib.
[src:rspec/ruby-programming-language] Ruby 2.4.0 includes performance improvements to hash table, Array#max, Array#min, and instance variable access.
[src:rspec/ruby-programming-language] A few notable changes in Ruby 2.6.0 include an experimental just-in-time compiler (JIT), and *RubyVM::AbstractSyntaxTree* (experimental).
[src:rspec/ruby-programming-language] A few notable changes in Ruby 2.7.0 include pattern Matching (experimental), REPL improvements, a compaction GC, and separation of positional and keyword arguments.
[src:rspec/ruby-programming-language] Ruby 3.0.0 was released on Christmas Day in 2020.
[src:rspec/ruby-programming-language] It is known as Ruby 3x3, which signifies that programs would run three times faster in Ruby 3.0 comparing to Ruby 2.0. and some had already been implemented in intermediate releases on the road from 2 to 3.
[src:rspec/ruby-programming-language] To achieve 3x3, Ruby 3 comes with MJIT, and later YJIT, Just-In-Time Compilers, to make programs faster, although they are described as experimental and remain disabled by default (enabled by flags at runtime).
[src:rspec/ruby-programming-language] Another goal of Ruby 3.0 is to improve concurrency and two more utilities Fibre Scheduler, and experimental Ractor facilitate the goal.
[src:rspec/ruby-programming-language] Ractor is light-weight and thread-safe as it is achieved by exchanging messages rather than shared objects.
[src:rspec/ruby-programming-language] Ruby 3.0 introduces RBS language to describe the types of Ruby programs for static analysis.
[src:rspec/ruby-programming-language] It is separated from general Ruby programs.
[src:rspec/ruby-programming-language] There are some syntax enhancements and library changes in Ruby 3.0 as well.
[src:rspec/ruby-programming-language] Ruby 3.1 was released on 25 December 2021.
[src:rspec/ruby-programming-language] It includes YJIT, a new, experimental, Just-In-Time Compiler developed by Shopify, to enhance the performance of real world business applications.
[src:rspec/ruby-programming-language] There are some syntax enhancements and other improvements in this release.
[src:rspec/ruby-programming-language] Network libraries for FTP, SMTP, IMAP, and POP are moved from default gems to bundled gems.
[src:rspec/ruby-programming-language] Ruby 3.2 was released on 25 December 2022.
[src:rspec/ruby-programming-language] It brings support for being run inside of a WebAssembly environment via a WASI interface.
[src:rspec/ruby-programming-language] Regular expressions also receives some improvements, including a faster, memoized matching algorithm to protect against certain ReDoS attacks, and configurable timeouts for regular expression matching.
[src:rspec/ruby-programming-language] Additional debugging and syntax features are also included in this release, which include syntax suggestion, as well as error highlighting.
[src:rspec/ruby-programming-language] The MJIT compiler has been re-implemented as a standard library module, while the YJIT, a Rust-based JIT compiler now supports more architectures on Linux.
[src:rspec/ruby-programming-language] Ruby 3.3 was released on 25 December 2023.
[src:rspec/ruby-programming-language] Ruby 3.3 introduces significant enhancements and performance improvements to the language.
[src:rspec/ruby-programming-language] Key features include the introduction of the Prism parser for portable and maintainable parsing, the addition of the pure-Ruby JIT compiler RJIT, and major performance boosts in the YJIT compiler.
[src:rspec/ruby-programming-language] Additionally, improvements in memory usage, the introduction of an M:N thread scheduler, and updates to the standard library contribute to a more efficient and developer-friendly Ruby ecosystem.
[src:rspec/ruby-programming-language] Ruby 3.4 was released on 25 December 2024.
[src:rspec/ruby-programming-language] Ruby 3.4 adds `it` block parameter reference, changes Prism as default parser, adds Happy Eyeballs Version 2 support to socket library, improves YJIT, adds modular Garbage Collector and so on.
[src:rspec/ruby-programming-language] It adds experimental ZJIT, a JIT written in Rust, and experimental "Ruby Box", a feature to provide separation about definitions.
[src:rspec/ruby-programming-language] It was decided to bump the version number to 4.0 instead of 3.5 to celebrate Rubys 30. birthday.
[src:rspec/ruby-programming-language] Matsumoto stated that Ruby is designed for programmer productivity and fun, following the principles of good user interface design.
[src:rspec/ruby-programming-language] At a Google Tech Talk in 2008 he said, "I hope to see Ruby help every programmer in the world to be productive, and to enjoy programming, and to be happy.
[src:rspec/ruby-programming-language] Matsumoto has said his primary design goal was to make a language that he himself enjoyed using, by minimizing programmer work and possible confusion.
[src:rspec/ruby-programming-language] If that personal standard remains consistent, there would be few surprises for those familiar with the standard.
[src:rspec/ruby-programming-language] Ruby is object-oriented: every value is an object, including classes and instances of types that many other languages designate as primitives (such as integers, Booleans, and "null").
[src:rspec/ruby-programming-language] Because everything in Ruby is an object, everything in Ruby has certain built-in abilities called methods.
[src:rspec/ruby-programming-language] Every function is a method and methods are always called on an object.
[src:rspec/ruby-programming-language] Methods defined at the top level scope become methods of the Object class.
[src:rspec/ruby-programming-language] Since this class is an ancestor of every other class, such methods can be called on any object.
[src:rspec/ruby-programming-language] They are also visible in all scopes, effectively serving as "global" procedures.
[src:rspec/ruby-programming-language] Ruby supports inheritance with dynamic dispatch, mixins and singleton methods (belonging to, and defined for, a single instance rather than being defined on the class).
[src:rspec/ruby-programming-language] Though Ruby does not support multiple inheritance, classes can import modules as mixins.
[src:rspec/ruby-programming-language] It has support for introspection, reflective programming, metaprogramming, and interpreter-based threads.
[src:rspec/ruby-programming-language] Ruby features dynamic typing, and supports parametric polymorphism.
[src:rspec/ruby-programming-language] According to the Ruby FAQ, the syntax is similar to Perl's and the semantics are similar to Smalltalk's, but the design philosophy differs greatly from Python's.
[src:rspec/ruby-programming-language] The syntax of Ruby is broadly similar to that of Perl and Python.
[src:rspec/ruby-programming-language] Class and method definitions are signaled by keywords, whereas code blocks can be defined by either keywords or braces.
[src:rspec/ruby-programming-language] In contrast to Perl, variables are not obligatorily prefixed with a sigil.
[src:rspec/ruby-programming-language] When used, the sigil changes the semantics of scope of the variable.
[src:rspec/ruby-programming-language] For practical purposes there is no distinction between expressions and statements.
[src:rspec/ruby-programming-language] Line breaks are significant and taken as the end of a statement; a semicolon may be equivalently used.
[src:rspec/ruby-programming-language] Unlike Python, indentation is not significant.
[src:rspec/ruby-programming-language] One of the differences from Python and Perl is that Ruby keeps all of its instance variables completely private to the class and only exposes them through accessor methods (`attr_writer`, `attr_reader`, etc.).
[src:rspec/ruby-programming-language] Unlike the "getter" and "setter" methods of other languages like C++ or Java, accessor methods in Ruby can be created with a single line of code via metaprogramming; however, accessor methods can also be created in the traditional fashion of C++ and Java.
[src:rspec/ruby-programming-language] As invocation of these methods does not require the use of parentheses, it is trivial to change an instance variable into a full function, without modifying a single line of calling code or having to do any refactoring achieving similar functionality to C# and VB.NET property members.
[src:rspec/ruby-programming-language] Python's property descriptors are similar, but come with a trade-off in the development process.
[src:rspec/ruby-programming-language] If one begins in Python by using a publicly exposed instance variable, and later changes the implementation to use a private instance variable exposed through a property descriptor, code internal to the class may need to be adjusted to use the private variable rather than the public property.
[src:rspec/ruby-programming-language] Ruby's design forces all instance variables to be private, but also provides a simple way to declare `set` and `get` methods.
[src:rspec/ruby-programming-language] This is in keeping with the idea that in Ruby, one never directly accesses the internal members of a class from outside the class; rather, one passes a message to the class and receives a response.
[src:rspec/ruby-programming-language] The original Ruby interpreter is often referred to as Matz's Ruby Interpreter or MRI.
[src:rspec/ruby-programming-language] This implementation is written in C and uses its own Ruby-specific virtual machine.
[src:rspec/ruby-programming-language] The standardized and retired Ruby 1.8 implementation was written in C, as a single-pass interpreted language.
[src:rspec/ruby-programming-language] Starting with Ruby 1.9, and continuing with Ruby 2.x and above, the official Ruby interpreter has been YARV ("Yet Another Ruby VM"), and this implementation has superseded the slower virtual machine used in previous releases of MRI.
[src:rspec/ruby-programming-language] As of 2026, there are a number of alternative implementations of Ruby, including JRuby, Rubinius, and mruby.
[src:rspec/ruby-programming-language] Each takes a different approach, with JRuby and Rubinius providing just-in-time compilation and mruby also providing ahead-of-time compilation.
[src:rspec/ruby-programming-language] The maturity of Ruby implementations tends to be measured by their ability to run the Ruby on Rails (Rails) framework, because it is complex to implement and uses many Ruby-specific features.
[src:rspec/ruby-programming-language] The point when a particular implementation achieves this goal is called "the Rails singularity".
[src:rspec/ruby-programming-language] The reference implementation, JRuby, and Rubinius are all able to run Rails unmodified in a production environment.
[src:rspec/ruby-programming-language] Matsumoto originally developed Ruby on the 4.3BSD-based Sony NEWS-OS 3.x, but later migrated his work to SunOS 4.x, and finally to Linux.
[src:rspec/ruby-programming-language] By 1999, Ruby was known to work across many different operating systems.
[src:rspec/ruby-programming-language] Modern Ruby versions and implementations are available on all major desktop, mobile and server-based operating systems.
[src:rspec/ruby-programming-language] Ruby is also supported across a number of cloud hosting platforms like Jelastic, Heroku, Google Cloud Platform and others.
[src:rspec/ruby-programming-language] Tools such as RVM and RBEnv, facilitate installation and partitioning of multiple ruby versions, and multiple 'gemsets' on one machine.
[src:rspec/ruby-programming-language] A Ruby package is called a "gem" and can be installed via the command line.
[src:rspec/ruby-programming-language] Most gems are libraries, though a few exist that are applications, such as IDEs.
[src:rspec/ruby-programming-language] There are over 100,000 Ruby gems hosted on RubyGems.org.
[src:rspec/ruby-programming-language] Many new and existing Ruby libraries are hosted on GitHub, a service that offers version control repository hosting for Git.
[src:rspec/ruby-programming-language] The Ruby Application Archive, which hosted applications, documentation, and libraries for Ruby programming, was maintained until 2013, when its function was transferred to RubyGems.
